)@@G@@         NYU EXEC TCF AND SKELETON  @]@@@@SPACE 15    @C@@@@            MV
)@@G@@      NYU EXEC 8 TCF AND SKELETON   @]@@@@SPACE 5     @B@@@@            MW
)@@G@@         NEW YORK UNIVERSITY  @B@@@@                     UHMC COMPUTER CMX
)@@G@@ENTER @]@@@@SPACE 10    @E@@@@                                    DUFF KMY
)@@G@@URLAND, SYSTEMS   @C@@@@                                    APRIL, 1973 MZ
)@@G@@@#@@@@4THE SKELETON     @F@@@@      OUR EXEC-8 SYSGEN SKELETON USES THE NA
)@@G@@EDITOR (@EDQ) TO DO MUCH@E@@@@ OF THE WORK SSG USUALLY DOES TO SET UP CONB
)@@G@@NFIG, THUS THE SSG@E@@@@ PORTION OF THE SYSGEN GOES MUCH QUICKER.  THE ONC
)@@G@@NLY OTHER   @F@@@@ BIG CHANGE IS THAT THE PROC'S HAVE BEEN GIVEN ELEMENTND
)@@G@@ NAMES LIKE @F@@@@ AACONFIG, AAPCT, AASMTAGS, ETC.  THIS ENABLES THE USENE
)@@G@@ OF SSG'S   @E@@@@ ALPHABETIZING CAPABILITIES, AND SIMPLIFIES THE SKELETNF
)@@G@@ON    @]@@@@ SOMEWHAT.  @[@@@@SPACE @G@@@@      A REL TAPE, AS SUCH, IS NG
)@@G@@NOT KEPT.  ALL THE FILES FOR A PARTICULAR @E@@@@ LEVEL OF THE EXEC (SAY,NH
)@@G@@ 31.159, OR 31.244) ARE KEPT ON A   @E@@@@ REMOVABLE DISC PACK, BY THEMSNI
)@@G@@ELVES, EACH SET WITH ITS OWN  @E@@@@ PROJECT-ID TO IDENTIFY IT.  AT THE NJ
)@@G@@CONCLUSION OF A SYSGEN, @F@@@@ ALL THE IMPORTANT FILES (PCF, TCF, RO, ANNK
)@@G@@D GEN) ARE SAVED TO     @#@@@@ TAPE USING @OUT. @[@@@@SPACE @F@@@@      NL
)@@G@@USING THIS METHOD, A MAXIMUM OF ONE TAPE (THE PRINT TAPE)   @F@@@@ IS NENM
)@@G@@EDED AT ANY TIME BY A NORMAL SYSGEN (EXCEPT WHEN WRITING    @F@@@@ THE BNN
)@@G@@OOT TAPE, WHICH IS COPIED TO A SECOND TAPE).  A MULTI-RUN   @F@@@@ SYSGENO
)@@G@@N WILL, OF COURSE, REQUIRE ONE PRINT TAPE FOR EACH RUN,     @C@@@@ IF THNP
)@@G@@E PRINTOUT HAS BEEN DIRECTED TO TAPE.     @[@@@@SPACE @E@@@@     RECENT NQ
)@@G@@ENHANCEMENTS HAVE BEEN MADE TO ALLOW FOR SEVERAL@E@@@@ DIFFERENT SYSGENSNR
)@@G@@ TO BE ABLE TO BE RUN AT ONCE, AND TO     @E@@@@ IMPLEMENT AUTOMATIC RESNS
)@@G@@TARTABILITY FOR EACH SYSGEN RUN.    @C@@@@ THE NORMAL SEQUENCE OF EVENTSNT
)@@G@@ IS A FOLLOWS:    @[@@@@SPACE @]@@@@COLUMN 6    @^@@@@  1. @START  GEN.SNU
)@@G@@TART  @E@@@@  2. 'WHOMP' STARTS, CATALOGUES SEVERAL FILES, AND GENERATESNV
)@@G@@@ @@@@     THE SYSGEN RUNSTREAM(S). @G@@@@  3. 'WHOMP' @START'S 'GEN0', NW
)@@G@@THE FIRST (OR ONLY) SYSGEN RUNSTREAM.     @G@@@@  4. 'GEN0' @PDP'S ANY PNX
)@@G@@ROC'S THAT MUST BE @PDP'ED (BASED ON SGS'S).    @G@@@@     EACH OF THE GNY
)@@G@@ENERATED RUNSTREAMS WILL HAVE A FILE CALLED RO<X>,    @G@@@@     WHERE <NZ
)@@G@@X> IS A NUMBER CORRESPONDING TO THE GEN RUN NUMBER, FOR     @G@@@@     UOA
)@@G@@SE AS A RELOCATABLE OUTPUT FILE, AND AS ASM$PF.  'GEN0' COPIES    @G@@@@OB
)@@G@@     THE LATEST PROCS INTO EACH OF THESE FILES, THEN STARTS ALL (IF ANY)OC
)@@G@@@ @@@@     OF THE OTHER GEN RUNS.   @F@@@@  5. THE LAST GEN RUN CREATES OD
)@@G@@A RUNSTREAM CALLED 'MAPRUN' WHICH   @A@@@@     IT STARTS JUST BEFORE FINOE
)@@G@@NING. @F@@@@  6. 'MAPRUN' WAITS FOR ALL THE GEN RUNS TO FIN, THEN COPIESOF
)@@G@@ ALL  @F@@@@     THE RB'S FROM THE VARIOUS RO<X> FILES INTO THE MAIN RO OG
)@@G@@FILE, @G@@@@     PERFORMS THE COLLECTION, WRITES THE BOOT TAPE, AND STAROH
)@@G@@TS 'ENDSYS'.@F@@@@  7. 'ENDSYS' COPIES ALL THE IMPORTANT FILES TO TAPE, OI
)@@G@@@PACKS THEM,@G@@@@     CREATES LISTINGS OF THE TCF, SKELETON, SGS'S, ETCOJ
)@@G@@., AND DELETES    @ @@@@     ALL THE UNNEEDED FILES.  @[@@@@SPACE @]@@@@OK
)@@G@@COLUMN 2    @F@@@@      EACH OF THE GEN RUNS HAS A BUILT-IN RESTART CAPAOL
)@@G@@BILITY IN   @E@@@@ THE FORM OF AN @SSG CALL AND A SKELETON WHICH SEARCHEOM
)@@G@@S THIS@E@@@@ RUN'S RO<X> FILE, COUNTING UP ALL THE RB'S IN THE FILE.    ON
)@@G@@@F@@@@ IF NO RB'S ARE FOUND, THE RUNSTREAM CONTINUES AS NORMAL:  IF 'N' OO
)@@G@@@E@@@@ RB'S EXIST, THE SKELETON DOES A @JUMP TO THE 'N'TH @ASM,   @ @@@@OP
)@@G@@ AND CONTINUES FROM THERE.    @]@@@@4THE TCF    @B@@@@      OUR TCF FOR OQ
)@@G@@31.244 IS ENCLOSED.  WE @F@@@@ RELY HEAVILY ON UNITED SOFTWARE'S DEMAND OR
)@@G@@INTERFACE PACKAGE, AND  @E@@@@ SINCE THIS IS A PROPRIETARY ITEM, WE COULOS
)@@G@@D NOT INCLUDE     @F@@@@ THE MAJOR CODE FOR IT ON THIS RELEASE TAPE.  HOOT
)@@G@@WEVER, SEVERAL    @G@@@@ ELEMENTS OF THE EXEC HAD TO BE MODIFIED TO LET OU
)@@G@@DMI WORK, AND SINCE     @G@@@@ ALL THE NECESSARY FIXES ARE 'HARD-WIRED,'OV
)@@G@@ SO TO SPEAK, INTO OUR TCF,   @F@@@@ (WHICH WILL BE THE CASE UNTIL SSG HOW
)@@G@@ANDLES MERGING OF TCF'S),     @F@@@@ IT WOULD BE A DIFFICULT TASK TO EDIOX
)@@G@@T THEM ALL OUT.  SO, KINDLY   @G@@@@ IGNORE ANY CORRECTIONS MENTIONING DOY
)@@G@@EMAND INTERFACE (DMI OR DI), AND    @D@@@@ ANY CALLS TO PROC'S LIKE DMICOZ
)@@G@@ON, DIISTR, DIOEND, ETC.@^@@@@3EXEC MODIFICATIONS     @F@@@@      WE HAVPA
)@@G@@E MADE NUMEROUS MODIFICATIONS/ENHANCEMENTS TO EXEC-8, @C@@@@ ALL OF WHICPB
)@@G@@H ARE EVIDENT IN THE ENCLOSED TCF.  @F@@@@ AN ATTEMPT HAS BEEN MADE TO PPC
)@@G@@ROPERLY DOCUMENT THE LOCAL CODE,    @F@@@@ BUT MOST OF THE PEOPLE WHO DIPD
)@@G@@D THE ORIGINAL WORK ON THIS STUFF   @E@@@@ ARE NO LONGER HERE, SO IT'S BPE
)@@G@@EEN A PROBLEM, IN SOME CASES, @D@@@@ FOR US TO FIGURE OUT WHAT SOME OF TPF
)@@G@@HE CODE IS FOR.   @D@@@@ A PARTIAL LIST OF IMPORTANT MODIFICATIONS FOLLOPG
)@@G@@WS.   @#@@@@2UNATTENDED MODE  @G@@@@      THERE ARE ONLY A FEW REASONS WPH
)@@G@@E CAN THINK OF THAT MIGHT PREVENT   @F@@@@ THE STANDARD EXEC FROM BEING PI
)@@G@@LEFT ALONE, TO RUN ITSELF WHEN NO   @A@@@@ OPERATOR CAN BE PRESENT ON-SIPJ
)@@G@@TE.   @[@@@@SPACE @]@@@@COLUMN 5    @C@@@@ 1. THE LOG TAPE MUST NOT REWIPK
)@@G@@ND ON EVERY BOOT. @A@@@@    WE HAVE CODE TO PREVENT THIS.   @[@@@@SPACE PL
)@@G@@@F@@@@ 2. TAPE MOUNTS - THIS ONE IS EASY: JUST DOWN ALL THE TAPE DRIVES PM
)@@G@@@^@@@@    EXCEPT THE LOG TAPE.@[@@@@SPACE @G@@@@ 3. REMOVABLE DISC MOUNTPN
)@@G@@S - WE TOOK CARE OF THIS, AS EXPLAINED BELOW.   @[@@@@SPACE @F@@@@ 4. UNPO
)@@G@@DEFINED ACCOUNTS - WE JUST REJECT THEM ALL, AUTOMATICALLY.  @[@@@@SPACE PP
)@@G@@@G@@@@ 5. TYPE-AND-READ CONSOLE MESSAGES - THESE FALL INTO TWO CATEGORIEPQ
)@@G@@S:    @G@@@@    THOSE FROM A USER PROGRAM (SUCH AS @MSG,W'S) AND THOSE FPR
)@@G@@ROM THE     @C@@@@    SYSTEM (SUCH AS HARDWARE ERROR MESSAGES).   @F@@@@PS
)@@G@@    WE TOOK CARE OF THE FORMER AS EXPLAINED BELOW, BUT THE LATTER @G@@@@PT
)@@G@@    STILL REQUIRE HUMAN INTERVENTION.  FOR THESE, WE LEAVE WITH OUR     PU
)@@G@@@F@@@@    USERS THE PHONE NUMBER OF AN OPERATOR WHO CAN BE CALLED, IF   PV
)@@G@@@#@@@@    NECESSARY.    @]@@@@COLUMN 2    @[@@@@SPACE @F@@@@      WHEN TPW
)@@G@@HE SYSTEM IS ABOUT TO BE LEFT UNATTENDED, THE OPERATOR@D@@@@ DOWNS ALL TPX
)@@G@@HE TAPE DRIVES, LOCKS OUT THE PRINTERS AND@G@@@@ PUNCHES, AND SETS JUMP PY
)@@G@@SWITCH 11.  JUMP SWITCH 11 HAS THE FOLLOWING    @]@@@@ EFFECTS:   @[@@@@PZ
)@@G@@SPACE @]@@@@COLUMN 10   @F@@@@      1. IT TURNS OFF ALL @MSG,W'S - THE UQA
)@@G@@SER RECEIVES A MESSAGE  @F@@@@         STATING 'SYSTEM IS UNATTENDED' - QB
)@@G@@OUR @TALK AND @STAT     @G@@@@         PROCESSORS ALSO RECOGNIZE JK 11, QC
)@@G@@AND GIVE SIMILAR MESSAGES.    @[@@@@SPACE @G@@@@      2. ANY REQUESTS FOQD
)@@G@@R REMOVABLE DISC PACKS WHICH ARE NOT ALREADY    @F@@@@         MOUNTED GQE
)@@G@@ET A FAC REJECT.  IF THE PACK IS UP, THOUGH, IT @ @@@@         MAY BE REQF
)@@G@@FERENCED.   @[@@@@SPACE @G@@@@      3. WE HAVE A RUN CALLED 'RECOV' WHICQG
)@@G@@H STARTS AFTER SYS ON EVERY   @F@@@@         BOOT.  IT CONTAINS THE @SECQH
)@@G@@URE,R THAT SYS NORMALLY HAS,  @E@@@@         AND EXECUTES A PROGRAM WHICQI
)@@G@@H ASKS THE OPERATOR     @E@@@@         ALL SORTS OF EMBARASSING QUESTIONQJ
)@@G@@S IN AN ATTEMPT TO@F@@@@         DETERMINE WHY THE SYSTEM HAS STOPPED.  QK
)@@G@@IT PUTS OUT A @LOG@F@@@@         MESSAGE WITH THIS INFORMATION, AND OUR QL
)@@G@@WEEKLY STATISTICS @G@@@@         RUN, 'STISTX', PICKS UP THIS INFORMATIOQM
)@@G@@N.  WHEN JK 11 IS SET,  @F@@@@         RECOV DOESN'T BOTHER ASKING ANY QQN
)@@G@@UESTIONS, AND PUTS OUT A@F@@@@         LOG MESSAGE SAYING 'SYSTEM UNATTEQO
)@@G@@NDED, STOP UNKNOWN.'    @[@@@@SPACE @F@@@@      4. OUR SYSTEM IS SET UP QP
)@@G@@TO PUT A MASTER HOLD ON ALL BATCH   @G@@@@         JOBS DURING A BOOT, UQQ
)@@G@@NTIL THE OPERATOR KEYS IN 'CS A', AND TO  @G@@@@         PREVENT ALL DEMQR
)@@G@@AND TERMINAL INITIALIZATION UNTIL HE KEYS IN    @G@@@@         'D ON'.  QS
)@@G@@IF THE SYSTEM IS UNATTENDED (JK 11 IS SET), THEN THIS @D@@@@         CODQT
)@@G@@E IS BYPASSED, AND ALL JOBS MAY START.    @#@@@@2THE ML KEYIN     @]@@@@QU
)@@G@@COLUMN 2    @F@@@@      ALSO FOR THIS 'STISTX' PROGRAM, WE HAVE INSTITUTQV
)@@G@@ED THE ML   @G@@@@ (MAINTENANCE LOG) KEYIN.  ANY TIME A PIECE OF HARDWARQW
)@@G@@E FAILS OR IS     @G@@@@ ACTING FUNNY, THE OPERATORS KEY IN THIS INFORMAQX
)@@G@@TION IN AN ML KEYIN.    @F@@@@ STISTX COLLECTS THESE KEYINS, AND PRINTS QY
)@@G@@A TABULATED LISTING     @F@@@@ AT THE END OF ITS REPORT.  THE SYSTEM MAKQZ
)@@G@@ES CERTAIN SYNTACTICAL  @F@@@@ CHECKS OF THE KEYIN (IN DKEY) TO MAKE SURRA
)@@G@@E IT WILL BE ACCEPTED   @F@@@@ BY STISTX: IF IT WON'T, THE OPERATOR GETSRB
)@@G@@ AN 'ML KEY ERROR'.     @E@@@@ FULL DOCUMENTATION ON THE ML KEYIN SYNTAXRC
)@@G@@ IS LOCATED IN THE@^@@@@ CODE ITSELF, IN DKEY.  @]@@@@2GENDATE    @F@@@@RD
)@@G@@      THIS FILE CONTAINS A PROGRAM CALLED 'GENDATESGS' WHICH IS   @G@@@@RE
)@@G@@ EXECUTED DURING A SYSGEN, AND PROVIDES SSG WITH THE DATE THE SYSGEN    RF
)@@G@@@G@@@@ WAS RUN.  THIS INFORMATION IS THEN ADDED TO THE EXEC ELEMENT E8IDRG
)@@G@@.     @G@@@@ THE GENDATE IS USED TO PREVENT THE OPERATOR FROM MISTAKENLYRH
)@@G@@ KEYING     @F@@@@ IN A DATE EARLIER THAN THE GENERATION DATE OF THE SYSRI
)@@G@@TEM, UNLESS @G@@@@ A JUMP SWITCH IS SET.  THE 'GD' KEYIN HAS ALSO BEEN ARJ
)@@G@@DDED TO DISPLAY   @#@@@@ THE GENDATE.     @^@@@@2C-KEYIN MODIFICATIONS  RK
)@@G@@@#@@@@1THE 'C ID' KEYIN @[@@@@SPACE @F@@@@      WE HAVE IMPLEMENTED A 'CRL
)@@G@@ ID' KEYIN, ALLOWING THE DISPLAY    @F@@@@ OF THE CURRENT EXEC LEVEL, LIRM
)@@G@@B LEVEL, MAX CORE, AVAILABLE CORE,  @G@@@@ BOOT TAPE(S), LIB TAPE(S), SERN
)@@G@@CURE DIRECTORY TAPE, AND EXPOOL SIZE.     @E@@@@ THIS DISPLAY ALSO REPLARO
)@@G@@CES THE 'MAX CORE' MESSAGE ON BOOTS.@[@@@@SPACE @#@@@@1SITEID CHANGES   RP
)@@G@@@[@@@@SPACE @F@@@@      IF THE FIRST CHARACTER FOLLOWING THE 'C' IS NOT RQ
)@@G@@A NUMBER,   @G@@@@ CKEY HAS BEEN MODIFIED TO ASSUME THAT A TTY SITEID ISRR
)@@G@@ TO BE CHANGED.   @F@@@@ EITHER THE TYPED-IN ID OR THE CONSOLE-ID MAY BERS
)@@G@@ CHANGED IN THIS  @F@@@@ MANNER, WITHOUT A SYSGEN BEING NECESSARY.  DOCURT
)@@G@@MENTATION CAN BE  @ @@@@ FOUND IN THE TCF FOR CKEY.   @[@@@@SPACE @ @@@@RU
)@@G@@2ACCOUNT NUMBER REJECTION     @E@@@@      AS MENTIONED ABOVE, CSP HAS BERV
)@@G@@EN MODIFIED TO REJECT   @F@@@@ ALL UNDEFINED ACCOUNT NUMBERS AUTOMATICALRW
)@@G@@LY, ELIMINATING THE     @F@@@@ PROBLEM OF OUTSTANDING 'UNDEFINED ACCT' MRX
)@@G@@ESSAGES ON THE SYSTEM   @F@@@@ CONSOLE.  THIS WAS ONE OF THE MOST IMPORTRY
)@@G@@ANT CHANGES TO ALLOW    @A@@@@ UNATTENDED OPERATION OF THE SYSTEM.@^@@@@RZ
)@@G@@2B-KEYIN MODIFICATION   @G@@@@      EVER SINCE LEVEL 25, THE 'B' KEYIN HSA
)@@G@@AS PERMITTED THE CHANGING     @F@@@@ OF THE MAX-OPEN LIMIT FOR BATCH JOBSB
)@@G@@S.  HOWEVER, THERE IS NO WAY  @E@@@@ TO FIND OUT WHAT THE CURRENT SETTINSC
)@@G@@G IS.  OUR MODIFICATIONS@E@@@@ PERMIT THIS, VIA A 'B' KEYIN WITH NO NUMBSD
)@@G@@ER SPECIFIED.     @]@@@@2REMOTE 1130@G@@@@      CODE HAS BEEN ADDED TO SSE
)@@G@@MTAGS AND TO THE REMOTE 1004 SYMBIONTS    @G@@@@ TO HANDLE THE IBM 1130 SF
)@@G@@AS A REMOTE DEVICE.  THE ONLY REAL PROBLEM WAS  @A@@@@ THE DIFFERENCE INSG
)@@G@@ BLOCK LENGTHS.   @#@@@@2PRIVILEGED MODE  @G@@@@      WE HAVE CHANGED THSH
)@@G@@E METHOD RUNS USE TO BECOME PRIVILEGED.  WE     @F@@@@ HAVE SET THINGS USI
)@@G@@P SUCH THAT IF THE TWELFTH CHARACTER OF A RUN'S @F@@@@ ACCOUNT NUMBER ISSJ
)@@G@@ A @, THEN THE PRIVILEGED BIT IN THAT RUN'S PCT @H@@@@ IS SET.  NOW, A @SK
)@@G@@ IS AN ILLEGAL CHARACTER IN AN ACCOUNT NUMBER, BUT THAT     @G@@@@ DOESNSL
)@@G@@'T BOTHER US.  WE PUT ALL OUR UTILITY @SECURE RUNS, ETC., WHICH   @F@@@@SM
)@@G@@ NEED TO BE PRIVILEGED IN SYS$*RUN$, AND GIVE THEM ACCOUNT NUMBERS@G@@@@SN
)@@G@@ ENDING IN 'OV' (FOR OVERHEAD).  THESE ACCOUNT NUMBERS DO NOT APPEAR    SO
)@@G@@@F@@@@ IN THE ACCOUNT$ FILE (BUT THEIR COUNTERPARTS ENDING IN @ DO).    SP
)@@G@@@G@@@@ THE ELEMENT 'CSTART' WAS THEN MODIFIED TO CHECK FOR THE FOLLOWINGSQ
)@@G@@:     @]@@@@COLUMN 9    @[@@@@SPACE @B@@@@     1. DOES THE RUN COME FROMSR
)@@G@@ SYS$*RUN$? @[@@@@SPACE @F@@@@     2. DOES ITS ACCOUNT NUMBER END IN 'OVSS
)@@G@@'?  NOTE THAT THE RUN   @G@@@@        MUST HAVE BEEN STARTED BY THE OPERST
)@@G@@ATOR FOR THIS TO BE TRUE.     @[@@@@SPACE @]@@@@COLUMN 2    @G@@@@ IF A SU
)@@G@@RUN PASSES THESE TESTS, THEN ITS ACCOUNT NUMBER IS CHANGED BY     @D@@@@SV
)@@G@@ CSTART TO END IN 'P@', AND CSN MARKS IT PRIVILEGED.  @[@@@@SPACE @F@@@@SW
)@@G@@      WE COULD, AT THIS POINT, REMOVE ALL THE CODE INVOLVED WITH  @G@@@@SX
)@@G@@ MAKING A RUN PRIVILEGED IF IT HAS SYS$*DLOC$ ASSIGNED WITH THE CORRECT SY
)@@G@@@G@@@@ KEYS, BUT US SYSTEMS FOLKS SOMETIMES HAVE A NEED TO DO STRANGE THSZ
)@@G@@INGS, @G@@@@ AND WE OFTEN DO THEM FROM DEMAND RUNS.  IF SOMEONE CAN FIGUTA
)@@G@@RE OUT A    @G@@@@ FOOLPROOF METHOD FOR JUST THE SYSTEMS PEOPLE TO BE PRTB

)@@G@@1]    @[@@@@*LOOP @[@@@@*END  @ @@@@*IF [PERFORM,1,1,1] = ALL     @ @@@@DO
)@@G@@*INCREMENT A TO [PROX,1,1]    @^@@@@*PROCESS PROC [P,A,1,1] @ @@@@*CREATDP
)@@G@@E SGS: ASMD [P,A,1,1]   @[@@@@*LOOP @D@@@@#ADD,P    [MSGFILE,1,2,1].    DQ
)@@G@@          . COPY PROCS  @B@@@@*INCREMENT A FROM [PROX,1,1]+1 TO [P]     DR
)@@G@@@ @@@@*PROCESS ELEMENT [P,A,1,1]    @ @@@@*CREATE SGS: ASMD [P,A,1,1]   DS
)@@G@@@[@@@@*LOOP @[@@@@*ELSE @^@@@@*IF [PERFORM,1,1,1]=TCF @#@@@@*CLEAR PROCYDT
)@@G@@ET    @^@@@@*INCREMENT A TO [T]     @B@@@@*IF ROW SEARCH FROM PROX FOR [DU

)@@G@@IS CLEAR    @D@@@@#ADD,P    [MSGFILE,1,2,1].              . COPY PROCS  DW
)@@G@@@]@@@@*SET PROCYET@[@@@@*END  @ @@@@*PROCESS ELEMENT [T,A,1,1]    @[@@@@DX
)@@G@@*END  @ @@@@*CREATE SGS: ASMD [T,A,1,1]   @[@@@@*LOOP @[@@@@*ELSE @F@@@@DY
)@@G@@*IF [PERFORM,1,1,1] = CONFIGURATION OR [PERFORM,1,1,1] = CONFIG   @^@@@@DZ
)@@G@@*PROCESS PROC AACONFIG  @ @@@@*CREATE SGS: ASMD AACONFIG    @[@@@@*END  EA
)@@G@@@ @@@@*SET LASTPROC TO [PROX,1,1]+1 @^@@@@*INCREMENT A TO [P]     @^@@@@EB
)@@G@@*SET THISPROC TO [*A]   @ @@@@*IF [*THISPROC]=[*LASTPROC]   @D@@@@#ADD,PEC
)@@G@@    [MSGFILE,1,2,1].              . COPY PROCS  @[@@@@*END  @B@@@@*IF COED
)@@G@@LUMN SEARCH FROM ASM FOR [P,A,1,1]  @B@@@@*IF ROW SEARCH FROM PROX FOR [EE
)@@G@@P,A,1,1]    @^@@@@*PROCESS PROC [P,A,1,1] @[@@@@*ELSE @ @@@@*PROCESS ELEEF
)@@G@@MENT [P,A,1,1]    @[@@@@*END  @ @@@@*CREATE SGS: ASMD [P,A,1,1]   @[@@@@EG
)@@G@@*ELSE @E@@@@*IF [PERFORM,1,1,1]=CONFIGURATION OR [PERFORM,1,1,1]=CONFIG EH
)@@G@@@C@@@@*IF NOT COLUMN SEARCH FROM DONTASM FOR [P,A,1,1]@B@@@@*IF COLUMN SEI
)@@G@@EARCH FROM CONFD FOR [P,A,1,1]@^@@@@*SET CONCARD TO [*CARD] @^@@@@*IF [CEJ
)@@G@@ONFD,CONCARD,2]   @ @@@@*INCREMENT LL TO [NEWCON]     @A@@@@*INCREMENT QEK
)@@G@@ TO [CONFD,CONCARD,2]   @B@@@@*IF [CONFD,CONCARD,2,Q] = [NEWCON,LL,1,1] EL
)@@G@@@E@@@@*IF NOT COLUMN SEARCH FROM ASMD FOR [CONFD,CONCARD,1,1]     @ @@@@EM
)@@G@@*CREATE SGS: ASMD [P,A,1,1]   @ @@@@*PROCESS ELEMENT [P,A,1,1]    @[@@@@EN
)@@G@@*END  @[@@@@*END  @[@@@@*LOOP @[@@@@*LOOP @[@@@@*END  @[@@@@*END  @[@@@@EO
)@@G@@*END  @[@@@@*END  @[@@@@*END  @[@@@@*LOOP @[@@@@*END  @[@@@@*END  @#@@@@EP
